The paper focuses on complex scene understanding using a new representation called scenarios, which is a data-driven representation consisting of sets of frequently co-occurring objects. This falls under computer vision (cs.CV) as it deals with understanding real-world scene images. The paper also introduces a novel matrix factorization method and a new neural network architecture, which falls under artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses content-based image retrieval and comparison, which falls under information retrieval (cs.IR) and natural language processing (cs.CL).
